r and critic Peter Kemp shows how modern writers are obsessed with the past. In a series of engaging and illuminating chapters, Retroland traces this novelistic preoccupation with history, from the imperial and the political to the personal and the literary. Featuring famous names from across the United Kingdom, United States, and the wider Anglophone world, ranging from Salman Rushdie to Sarah Waters, Toni Morrison to Hilary Mantel, this is a work of remarkable synthesis and clarity—a wonderfully readable and enjoyably opinionated guide to our current literary landscape.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aEnglish fictionxHistory and criticism. 0aEnglish fictiony20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aEnglish fictiony21st centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aHistory in literature. 0aLiterature and history. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Modern / 20th Century .2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311074978640uhttps://doi.org/10.12987/9780300275025?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300275025423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780300275025/original  a978-3-11-074978-6  Yale University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles